classes.brief:
Clique branching for binary variable sets
Copyright (C) 2002, IBM Corporation and others. All Rights Reserved.
This code is licensed under the terms of the Eclipse Public License (EPL).

CbcClique: Branching for cliques (sets of binary variables with
at most one at its "strong" value). Generalizes binary SOS1.

Standard form: x1 + x2 + ... + xn <= 1 (all strong at 1)
General form allows negated variables (y_j = 1 - x_j).

Member types (type_[i]):
- 1: SOS-style, coefficient +1, strong value is 1
- 0: Non-SOS, coefficient -1, strong value is 0

- whenCutGenerator_: Frequency (every N nodes, -100=disabled, -99=root only)
- depthCutGenerator_: Depth-based triggering
- switches_: Bit flags for various options (normal, atSolution, timing, etc.)

Central parameter collection for Cbc algorithm control
Copyright (C) 2007, Lou Hafer, IBM Corporation and others.
This code is licensed under the terms of the Eclipse Public License (EPL).

CbcParameters: Master class holding all Cbc solver parameters.
Used by cbc-generic to configure and control the MIP solver.

Major subsystems configured:
- Cut generators: Gomory, MIR, Probing, Clique, FlowCover, etc.
- Heuristics: FPump, RINS, RENS, DINS, Diving variants, VND, etc.
- Search strategy: Node selection, preprocessing, orbital branching
- Limits: Time, nodes, gap tolerance, solution count

Includes instances of CGL cut generators and Cbc heuristics.
Links to ClpParameters for underlying LP solver control.

Key methods:
- init(): Initialize with strategy preset
- setModel(): Associate with CbcModel
- Various getters/setters for each parameter category

Strategy presets provide common configurations:
- Default aggressive cutting at root
- Balanced cut/heuristic emphasis
- Heuristic-focused for quick solutions

classes.name: CbcSOS
classes.brief:
Special Ordered Sets (SOS) Type 1 and Type 2 branching
Copyright (C) 2002, IBM Corporation and others. All Rights Reserved.
This code is licensed under the terms of the Eclipse Public License (EPL).

CbcSOS: Branching for Special Ordered Sets (Beale & Tomlin, 1970):

SOS Type 1: At most ONE variable can be nonzero
- Common for selection between alternatives (choose one option)
- SUM x_i <= 1 (or = 1 for exactly one)
- Binary SOS1 is a special case of clique

SOS Type 2: At most TWO CONSECUTIVE variables can be nonzero
- Used for piecewise linear approximation (interpolation)
- Variables ordered by weights; sum to 1
- Represents point between two breakpoints
